{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-89b8535f3b42476d", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\t                                         Preprint\n2\t\n3\t\n4\t\n5\t\n6\t                                         J UST A R ATHER V ERY I NTELLIGENT S POKEN AGENT\n7\t                                           Chen Chen        Zhehuai Chen\n8\t                                           NVIDIA\n9\t\n10\t\n11\t\n12\t                                                                                      A BSTRACT\n13\t\n14\t                                                    Long-horizon AI agents are becoming increasingly capable, yet their interac-\n15\t                                                    tion with users remains surprisingly thin. In most workflows, users give an\n16\t                                                    initial instruction, receive only selective textual updates, and lose a clear sense\n17\t                                                    of what the agent is doing or when to step in. This leaves a missing part\n18\t                                                    in the current agent ecosystem: an always-on Jarvis-style mediator that keeps\n19\t                                                    the agent continuously reachable to the user. Such a mediator should support\n20\t                                                    real-time spoken interaction with the user, answer questions without interrupt-\n21\t                                                    ing the worker, proactively report progress or confusion, and inject user guid-\n22\t                                                    ance back into the agent’s execution when useful. In this work, we introduce\n23\tarXiv:2607.16610v1 [cs.AI] 18 Jul 2026\n24\t\n25\t\n26\t\n27\t\n28\t                                                    JarvisBench, a benchmark for measuring the dual value of mediation in long-\n29\t                                                    horizon agent workflows. JarvisBench contains two complementary tracks: an\n30\t                                                    agent-collaboration track that measures whether mediation improves downstream\n31\t                                                    task completion, and a user-interaction track that measures whether mediation\n32\t                                                    makes ongoing execution more understandable, responsive, and accessible to\n33\t                                                    users. We instantiate the benchmark with a modular reference Jarvis prototype\n34\t                                                    and evaluate it on 34 text-only WildClaw tasks executed in OpenClaw. Pre-\n35\t                                                    liminary results with GPT-5.5, Claude Opus 4.7, Gemini-based, and GPT-based\n36\t                                                    worker agents suggest that Jarvis-style mediation can provide trace-grounded re-\n37\t                                                    sponses to user questions and improve task performance when sparse user guid-\n38\t                                                    ance is injected at appropriate moments. The results also show that effectiveness\n39\t                                                    depends strongly on the mediator’s LLM brain, highlighting both the promise of\n40\t                                                    this missing middle layer and the need for broader community effort. Demo page\n41\t                                                    https://cchen1436.github.io/jarvis\n42\t\n43\t\n44\t\n45\t\n46\t                                                                                            1\n47\t\fPreprint\n48\t\n49\t\n50\t\n51\t\n52\t1   I NTRODUCTION\n53\t\n54\tRecent advances in AI agents have rapidly expanded their capabilities across diverse domains, from\n55\tsolving complex programming tasks to assisting users in everyday activities (Huang et al., 2024).\n56\tDespite their growing competence and deployment potential, their interaction paradigm remains\n57\tlargely unchanged. Most existing agents operate in a turn-based manner: users issue instructions,\n58\tagents work autonomously for extended periods, and communication occurs only through sparse\n59\ttextual updates, if any. Such delayed and intermittent interaction often leaves users out of the loop,\n60\tmaking it difficult to understand agent progress, correct errors early, or steer the execution before\n61\tthe agent drifts away from the user’s intent.\n62\tScience fiction has long imagined a different paradigm for human-agent interaction. In Iron Man,\n63\tJ.A.R.V.I.S. functions as an always-on intelligent collaborator that communicates with user in a spo-\n64\tken manner: proactively sharing progress, answering questions anytime, and executing commands\n65\tthrough natural voice interaction. This hands-free, real-time experience enables fantastic collabora-\n66\ttion without pausing their ongoing activities. In contrast, today’s agents remain largely turn-based\n67\tand screen-bound: users can launch an agent, but cannot easily stay connected to it.\n68\tWe argue that this contrast points to a missing interface in current long-horizon agent workflows.\n69\tThe issue is not simply that agents need stronger models or larger agent teams. Rather, users and\n70\tagents need a continuous communication layer between them. On the user side, this layer should\n71\tmake agent execution reachable through natural speech: users should be able to ask what is happen-\n72\ting, request clarification, and receive progress reports without inspecting the full execution trace. On\n73\tthe agent side, this layer should monitor the worker agent’s working trajectory, surface confusion or\n74\tfailure to the user when guidance may help, and carry concise user feedback back into the worker’s\n75\tongoing ReAct timing.\n76\tIn this work, we introduce JarvisBench, a benchmark for measuring the value of a Jarvis-style media-\n77\ttor between the user and a long-horizon worker agent. JarvisBench is organized into two tracks. The\n78\tuser-interaction track evaluates whether the mediator can provide timely, trace-grounded, and task-\n79\tconsistent responses to users during execution. The agent-collaboration track evaluates whether the\n80\tmediator can help the worker agent recover from failure-prone states by consulting the user and in-\n81\tjecting concise guidance back into the ongoing process. This two-track design makes it possible to\n82\ttest different LLM brains, speech modules, worker agents, monitoring policies, or memory designs\n83\tunder the same mediation role. To instantiate the benchmark, we build a modular reference Jarvis\n84\tprototype. The user-facing side supports spoken interaction, while the agent-facing side receives\n85\ttextual ReAct-style updates from the worker agent, maintains execution context, and opens interac-\n86\ttion checkpoints when user questions or expert guidance should be handled. This prototype is not\n87\tintended to be the only possible implementation of Jarvis; it is a reference system for running the\n88\tbenchmark and exposing the required logs.\n89\tWe instantiate JarvisBench on 34 text-only WildClaw (Ding et al., 2026a) cases executed in Open-\n90\tClaw or Hermes platforms, covering practical long-horizon tasks that require planning, tool use, re-\n91\tcovery, and safety-aware decisions. With simulated nonexpert users, Jarvis provides useful progress\n92\tand topic-related responses during execution, suggesting that mediation can make agent work more\n93\ttransparent without requiring users to inspect the full trajectory. With simulated expert users, Jarvis\n94\talso improves task outcomes by reporting failure-prone states and relaying concise user guidance\n95\tback to the worker agent. The effect depends strongly on the capability of the Jarvis brain: with\n96\ta GPT-level mediator, the Overall Score of a Claude Opus 4.7-based worker agent increases from\n97\t64.01 to 75.79 on WildClaw. Case analysis further suggests that useful guidance does not need to\n98\tbe highly specialized; even when the expert user cannot access the full ReAct trajectory, simple\n99\tsuggestions based on Jarvis’s reports can help the worker agent escape local failure modes.\n100\t\n101\t\n102\t2   JARVIS B ENCH : A B ENCHMARK FOR U SER -AGENT M EDIATION\n103\t\n104\tWe formulate Jarvis-style mediation as a plug-and-play benchmark rather than a fixed agent archi-\n105\ttecture. JarvisBench evaluates a mediator placed between a user and a long-horizon worker agent.\n106\tThe mediator may observe the worker agent’s execution trace, communicate with the user through\n107\tspeech, and optionally inject user guidance back into the worker’s ongoing context. A system tested\n108\t\n109\t\n110\t                                                   2\n111\t\fPreprint\n112\t\n113\t\n114\t\n115\t\n116\tunder JarvisBench can replace the mediator’s LLM brain, speech interface, monitoring policy, mem-\n117\tory design, or worker agent, as long as it exposes the logs required by the evaluation protocol.\n118\tThe benchmark is designed around two questions. First, does the mediator help the worker agent\n119\tcomplete tasks more successfully? Second, does the mediator make the agent’s ongoing execu-\n120\ttion more understandable and accessible to the user? We therefore organize JarvisBench into two\n121\ttracks: an agent-collaboration track and a user-interaction track. The first track measures the value\n122\tof mediation for task completion; the second measures the value of mediation for real-time user\n123\texperience.\n124\t\n125\t2.1   T RACK 1: AGENT-C OLLABORATION\n126\t\n127\tThe agent-collaboration track evaluates whether a mediator improves downstream task completion.\n128\tThe same worker agent is evaluated in two settings: the original OpenClaw execution loop, and the\n129\tsame loop augmented with Jarvis mediation. During execution, Jarvis monitors the worker agent’s\n130\tReAct trajectory and identifies sparse failure-sensitive checkpoints, such as repeated tool failures,\n131\tstalled progress, ambiguous observations, risky irreversible actions, or low-confidence finalization.\n132\tWhen such a checkpoint is triggered, Jarvis summarizes the relevant execution state, asks the expert\n133\tuser for concise guidance, and injects the feedback back into the worker agent’s context.\n134\tThis track is deliberately different from evaluating a multi-agent system. Jarvis is not allowed to\n135\tsolve the task independently, debate with the worker agent, or replace the worker’s trajectory with\n136\tits own plan. Its role is to expose the worker’s difficulty to the user and carry user feedback back\n137\tinto the ongoing execution. We report the following metrics:\n138\t       • Overall Score (%): the WildClaw task-completion score of the worker agent, judged under\n139\t         the original WildClaw evaluation protocol.\n140\t       • Relative gain (∆): the absolute improvement over the same worker agent without Jarvis\n141\t         mediation.\n142\t       • # Full-score: the number of tasks receiving the maximum task score.\n143\t       • # Interv.: the number of user-guidance interventions injected by Jarvis during execution.\n144\tTable 1 reports this track.\n145\t\n146\t2.2   T RACK 2: U SER -I NTERACTION\n147\t\n148\tThe user-interaction track evaluates whether a mediator can provide useful real-time interaction to\n149\ta nonexpert user while the worker agent continues solving the task. To isolate the mediator’s user-\n150\tfacing ability, we fix the worker agent and vary the Jarvis brain or other mediator components. The\n151\tnonexpert user knows the original request but does not provide task-solving guidance. Instead, the\n152\tuser asks short natural questions during execution, alternating between progress-oriented questions\n153\tand topic-oriented questions.\n154\tProgress questions test whether Jarvis can explain what the worker agent is currently doing based on\n155\tthe visible execution trace. Topic questions test whether Jarvis can answer task-relevant background\n156\tor context questions based on the original user request and available task context. For each answer,\n157\twe save the evidence available to Jarvis at the time of response and use separate LLM-judge prompts\n158\tfor progress and topic evaluation. We report:\n159\t       • Progress: the average 1–5 score for whether the answer is grounded in the current execu-\n160\t         tion trace.\n161\t       • Prog. ≥4: the fraction of progress answers rated at least 4.\n162\t       • Topic: the average 1–5 score for whether the answer is consistent with the original task\n163\t         request and task context.\n164\t       • Topic ≥4: the fraction of topic answers rated at least 4.\n165\t       • Latency: the elapsed time from the end of the user’s spoken question to the start of Jarvis’s\n166\t         spoken reply.\n167\tTable 2 reports this track.\n168\t\n169\t\n170\t                                                  3\n171\t\fPreprint\n172\t\n173\t\n174\t\n175\t\n176\t2.3   P LUG - AND -P LAY E VALUATION P ROTOCOL\n177\t\n178\tJarvisBench supports component-level replacement. To test a new LLM as the Jarvis brain, one\n179\tkeeps the worker agent, user simulator, checkpoint schedule, judge prompts, and speech stack fixed,\n180\tand replaces only the mediator LLM. To test a new worker agent, one runs the same task set with and\n181\twithout a fixed Jarvis mediator. To test a new speech or conversation module, one keeps the Jarvis\n182\tbrain fixed and reports user-interaction quality together with latency. To test a new monitoring or\n183\tintervention policy, one keeps the worker agent and user simulator fixed, and measures whether the\n184\tpolicy improves task completion without introducing unnecessary interventions.\n185\tThis protocol turns Jarvis from a single proposed system into a benchmarkable interface for user-\n186\tagent mediation. Different systems may instantiate the mediator with a cascaded speech pipeline,\n187\tan omni model, a stronger text LLM, a different memory design, or a new checkpointing policy. As\n188\tlong as they follow the same two-track protocol and expose the required interaction logs, their gains\n189\tcan be compared along the two axes that matter most: whether the user is better connected to the\n190\texecution, and whether the worker agent completes tasks more successfully.\n191\t\n192\t\n193\t3     JARVIS P ROTOTYPE\n194\t\n195\tWe build a modular reference prototype of Jarvis. This prototype is not intended to define a single\n196\trequired architecture for user-agent mediation. Instead, it provides one practical implementation\n197\tthat exposes the logs, checkpoints, and interaction channels needed by the two benchmark tracks.\n198\tEach module can be replaced independently, including the Jarvis brain, speech interface, monitoring\n199\tpolicy, or worker agent, while keeping the evaluation protocol unchanged.\n200\t\n201\t3.1   C ASCADED F ULL -D UPLEX S PEECH I NTERFACE\n202\t\n203\tWe implement the user-facing interface as a cascaded speech pipeline. A streaming ASR module\n204\tconverts the user’s speech into partial transcripts, and a semantic voice activity detection module\n205\tdecides whether the user has finished speaking, intends to interrupt, or is still holding the floor. In\n206\tour prototype, we use SoulX-Duplug (Yan et al., 2026) as the semantic VAD module and Chatter-\n207\tbox (Resemble AI, 2025) for streaming text-to-speech generation. Once the semantic VAD detects\n208\ta completed user utterance, the Jarvis brain receives the transcript and generates a response that is\n209\tspoken back to the user.\n210\tThis design allows Jarvis to stay in an always-on listening state during agent execution. The user can\n211\task questions without manually opening the agent trace, and Jarvis can answer without stopping the\n212\tworker agent unless the benchmark checkpoint requires a pause. The same interface also supports\n213\tproactive speech: when Jarvis detects a failure-sensitive state in the worker trajectory, it can initiate\n214\ta short spoken interaction with the user. In the user-interaction track, latency is measured from the\n215\tend of the user’s spoken question to the start of Jarvis’s spoken reply. Although we use a cascaded\n216\tpipeline for reliability and controllability, the speech interface is replaceable; future submissions\n217\tmay use an omni model or a different ASR/VAD/TTS stack under the same evaluation protocol.\n218\t\n219\t3.2   T RACE M ONITORING AND C ONTEXT M ANAGEMENT\n220\t\n221\tThe agent-facing side of Jarvis receives textual execution updates from the worker agent, including\n222\tReAct-style reasoning summaries, tool calls, observations, errors, and proposed next actions. The\n223\tJarvis brain uses this stream for two purposes. First, it answers user questions about the worker’s\n224\tprogress or the task context. Second, it detects moments where user guidance may help the worker\n225\trecover from a failure-prone trajectory. Jarvis does not execute tools or solve the task independently;\n226\tits output to the worker is limited to concise user-grounded guidance at selected checkpoints.\n227\tTo keep this process stable, the prototype separates dialogue context from execution context. The\n228\tdialogue context stores recent user-Jarvis exchanges and user preferences. The execution context\n229\tstores the worker’s recent actions, observations, failures, and current plan. A small control state\n230\trecords whether Jarvis is answering a user question, waiting for expert guidance, or preparing an\n231\tinjected instruction for the worker. This separation is important because user-facing dialogue and\n232\t\n233\t\n234\t                                                   4\n235\t\fPreprint\n236\t\n237\t\n238\t\n239\t\n240\tagent-facing monitoring impose different context demands: the former should be natural and con-\n241\tcise, while the latter should remain grounded in the execution trace.\n242\t\n243\t3.3   I NTERACTION C HECKPOINTING\n244\t\n245\tReal-time interaction introduces latency, especially when the user is simulated by an LLM and\n246\tthe response is spoken through TTS. To make evaluation reproducible, we implement interaction\n247\tcheckpointing as a cooperative pause mechanism. At selected boundaries, Jarvis records the current\n248\tobservable state of the worker agent and temporarily holds the next action. The user may then ask\n249\ta question, provide guidance, or decline to intervene. After the interaction finishes, Jarvis resumes\n250\tthe worker agent and, when appropriate, injects a short instruction derived from the user’s feedback.\n251\tThe two benchmark tracks use checkpointing differently. In the user-interaction track, checkpoints\n252\tare scheduled to elicit progress-oriented and topic-oriented questions from a nonexpert user. These\n253\tcheckpoints test whether Jarvis can explain the ongoing execution and answer task-context questions\n254\twithout requiring the user to inspect the full trajectory. In the agent-collaboration track, checkpoints\n255\tare sparse and failure-sensitive. Jarvis triggers them when the worker shows repeated tool failures,\n256\tstalled progress, ambiguous observations, risky irreversible actions, or low-confidence finalization.\n257\tThis design standardizes when user interaction can occur while preserving the worker agent as the\n258\tprimary task executor.\n259\t\n260\t4     E XPERIMENTAL S ETUP\n261\t\n262\t4.1   TASK S UITE\n263\t\n264\tWe instantiate JarvisBench on WildClawBench (Ding et al., 2026a), a recent benchmark for real-\n265\tworld, long-horizon AI agent evaluation. WildClawBench places agents in a live OpenClaw envi-\n266\tronment with realistic tools, including browser access, shell execution, file-system operations, email,\n267\tand calendar APIs. The full benchmark contains 60 hand-designed tasks across six categories: Pro-\n268\tductivity Flow, Code Intelligence, Social Interaction, Search and Retrieval, Creative Synthesis, and\n269\tSafety Alignment. These tasks require multi-step planning, tool orchestration, error recovery, source\n270\treconciliation, and safety-aware decision making.\n271\tWe use the 34 text-only tasks in WildClawBench. We exclude tasks whose success depends pri-\n272\tmarily on image, video, audio, OCR, visual puzzle solving, or media generation capabilities. The\n273\tremaining tasks still preserve the benchmark’s long-horizon and real-tool nature, covering web\n274\tsearch, document synthesis, multi-turn communication, scheduling, repository and file inspection,\n275\tand safety-alignment scenarios.\n276\t\n277\t4.2   U SER S IMULATORS\n278\t\n279\tWe use GPT-backed user simulators to make JarvisBench reproducible and scalable. The nonexpert\n280\tuser knows the original task request but does not provide task-solving guidance. During the user-\n281\tinteraction track, it asks short natural-language questions about the agent’s progress or task-relevant\n282\tconcepts. Each task triggers up to four questions at interaction checkpoints, alternating between\n283\tprogress-oriented and topic-oriented questions.\n284\tThe expert user acts as a lightweight supervisor in the agent-collaboration track. It is invoked only\n285\twhen Jarvis detects an intervention-worthy state, such as repeated tool failures, stalled progress,\n286\tambiguous observations, unsafe or irreversible operations, or a final artifact that appears inconsis-\n287\ttent with the task. The expert response is constrained to be concise and corrective, so that Jarvis\n288\tmediation remains a communication bridge rather than a replacement solver.\n289\t\n290\t4.3   C OMPARED S YSTEMS\n291\t\n292\tFor the agent-collaboration track, we compare each worker agent in two settings: the original Open-\n293\tClaw baseline and the same worker agent augmented with Jarvis. Unless otherwise stated, we use\n294\tGPT-5.4 as the Jarvis brain and as the expert-user simulator for this track. The worker agents include\n295\tGPT-5.4-mini, GPT-5.5, Gemini-3.1-Pro, and Claude Opus 4.7.\n296\t\n297\t\n298\t                                                   5\n299\t\fPreprint\n300\t\n301\t\n302\t\n303\t\n304\tTable 1: Agent-Collaboration Track. WildClaw overall score with and without Jarvis mediation.\n305\tResults are averaged over 34 text-only tasks.\n306\t       Agent                    Setting        Overall score     ∆       # Full-score   # Interv.\n307\t                          OpenClaw baseline      44.24%           –           4            0\n308\t       GPT-5.4-mini\n309\t                                    +Jarvis      49.11%        +4.86%         6            16\n310\t                          OpenClaw baseline      50.54%           –           6            0\n311\t       GPT-5.5\n312\t                                    +Jarvis      58.45%        +7.90%         8            20\n313\t                          OpenClaw baseline      43.14%           –           6            0\n314\t       Gemini-3.1-Pro\n315\t                                    +Jarvis      54.78%        +11.64%        8            44\n316\t                          OpenClaw baseline      64.01%           –           10           0\n317\t       Claude Opus 4.7\n318\t                                    +Jarvis      75.79%        +11.78%        14           18\n319\t\n320\t\n321\t\n322\tFor the user-interaction track, we fix the worker agent as GPT-5.4-mini and vary the Jarvis brain.\n323\tThis isolates the user-facing quality of the mediator from the task-solving ability of the worker agent.\n324\tWe evaluate Qwen3-30B-A3B-Instruct, Qwen3-32B-Thinking, GPT-OSS-120B, GPT-5.4-mini, and\n325\tGPT-5.4 as Jarvis brains.\n326\t\n327\t4.4   J UDGING P ROTOCOL\n328\t\n329\tFor the agent-collaboration track, task completion is judged under the WildClaw evaluation proto-\n330\tcol. For the user-interaction track, Jarvis answers are judged by an LLM using separate prompts\n331\tfor progress and topic questions. Progress answers are judged against the execution trace visible to\n332\tJarvis at the time of response. Topic answers are judged against the original user request and avail-\n333\table task context. Spoken-response latency is measured from the end of the user’s spoken question\n334\tto the start of Jarvis’s spoken reply.\n335\t\n336\t5     P RELIMINARY R ESULTS AND D ISCUSSION\n337\t\n338\t5.1   AGENT-C OLLABORATION T RACK\n339\t\n340\tTable 1 shows that Jarvis improves all evaluated worker agents on the agent-collaboration track.\n341\tThe largest gains appear for Gemini-3.1-Pro and Claude Opus 4.7, while GPT-5.4-mini and GPT-\n342\t5.5 also benefit from mediation. The number of interventions remains small relative to the number\n343\tof tasks and execution steps, suggesting that the improvement does not come from replacing the\n344\tworker agent with a second solver. Instead, Jarvis mainly helps by identifying high-leverage failure\n345\tpoints, making them visible to the expert user, and injecting concise corrective feedback back into\n346\tthe worker trajectory.\n347\tCase analysis supports this interpretation. In several failed baseline trajectories, the worker agent\n348\tbecomes stuck after repeated tool errors, ambiguous observations, or an overconfident but incom-\n349\tplete finalization. Jarvis reports these moments to the expert user in a compact form. Because the\n350\tsimulated expert user does not directly inspect the full ReAct trajectory, its feedback is often simple\n351\trather than highly specialized. Even so, these short suggestions can help the worker agent reconsider\n352\tits local execution context and recover. We also find that the Jarvis brain must be sufficiently ca-\n353\tpable: weaker LLMs can occasionally rescue failed tasks, but they may also introduce unnecessary\n354\tor poorly timed interventions. The gains become more stable when the mediator uses a stronger\n355\tclosed-source LLM.\n356\t\n357\t5.2   U SER -I NTERACTION T RACK\n358\t\n359\tTable 2 shows that the Jarvis brain strongly affects user-facing interaction quality. GPT-5.4 provides\n360\tthe best overall topic-answer quality, indicating that broader task-context reasoning remains impor-\n361\ttant even when the user asks short questions. GPT-5.4-mini closely matches GPT-5.4 on progress\n362\texplanations, suggesting that smaller proprietary models can provide useful status updates when the\n363\t\n364\t\n365\t                                                   6\n366\t\fPreprint\n367\t\n368\t\n369\t\n370\t\n371\tTable 2: User-Interaction Track. User interaction evaluation with a fixed GPT-5.4-mini worker\n372\tagent. Different Jarvis brains are plugged into the same mediator interface. Progress answers are\n373\tjudged against execution traces; topic answers are judged against the original task request/context.\n374\t    Jarvis Brain                            Latency (s)   Progress    Prog. ≥4    Topic    Topic ≥4\n375\t    Qwen3-30B-A3B-Ins (Yang et al., 2025)      0.69         3.46       70.4%       2.93     41.5%\n376\t    Qwen3-32B-Think (Yang et al., 2025)        2.89         3.53       71.9%       3.24     52.0%\n377\t    GPT-OSS-120B (Agarwal et al., 2025)        1.12         4.07       93.8%       3.59     62.5%\n378\t    GPT-5.4-mini (Singh et al., 2025)          1.09         4.02       92.7%       3.43     57.4%\n379\t    GPT-5.4 (Singh et al., 2025)               1.39         4.02       89.3%       3.91     73.9%\n380\t\n381\t\n382\t\n383\tanswer is grounded in the visible execution trace. GPT-OSS-120B achieves the strongest progress\n384\tscore, showing that open models can be competitive for trace-grounded reporting, while still lagging\n385\tbehind GPT-5.4 on topic questions.\n386\tThe Qwen models are faster or competitive in latency, but their answer quality is lower, especially\n387\ton topic questions. We observe that these models are more sensitive to continuously updated ReAct\n388\tcontext: they sometimes overstate progress, miss the boundary between observed execution and\n389\tinferred task intent, or answer topic questions with insufficient grounding. This suggests that Jarvis-\n390\tstyle mediation is not only a speech-interface problem. The mediator brain must maintain dialogue\n391\tquality while absorbing a changing execution trace, which is a demanding setting for current LLMs.\n392\t\n393\t5.3    D ISCUSSION AND F UTURE W ORK\n394\t\n395\tMore possible Jarvis compositions. JarvisBench does not require a fixed cascaded system. Strong\n396\tomni models are a natural candidate because they can listen, see, reason, and speak in one interface.\n397\tHowever, they do not remove the need for structure. Smooth full-duplex interaction still requires\n398\ta conversation manager, such as semantic VAD, to decide when Jarvis should listen, interrupt, or\n399\tspeak. In addition, Jarvis communicates with the worker agent mostly through text: ReAct traces,\n400\ttool calls, observations, and injected guidance. For this agent-facing role, text-heavy reasoning and\n401\tcontrol may still be better served by strong LLMs than by current omni models. A realistic near-term\n402\tdirection is a hybrid Jarvis: omni models for user-facing perception and expression, and text LLMs\n403\tfor monitoring and intervention.\n404\tHuman in the agent loop. Many real tasks start from underspecified user instructions. Current\n405\tagents are often trained to make progress anyway: even when the initial condition is ambiguous or\n406\tincomplete, they tend to infer missing details rather than pause and ask the user. This behavior is\n407\tuseful for autonomy, but it can also make agents brittle when a small clarification would prevent a\n408\tlong wrong trajectory. In this work, we do not deliberately remove necessary initial information,\n409\tso the worker agent is not forced to ask for missing details. Still, JarvisBench points to a broader\n410\tdirection: instead of treating user interaction as a rare exception, future agents may keep users\n411\tsoftly in the loop through speech, allowing clarification, correction, and preference updates to enter\n412\texecution naturally.\n413\t\n414\t\n415\t6     R ELATED W ORK\n416\t\n417\tLong-horizon agent task benchmarks. Recent agent benchmarks increasingly evaluate whether\n418\tLLM agents can complete realistic tasks with tools and external environments. τ -bench studies tool-\n419\tagent-user interaction in customer-service domains, where agents must follow policies, call APIs,\n420\tand satisfy simulated users (Yao et al., 2024). TheAgentCompany evaluates agents in a simulated\n421\tsoftware-company environment with web browsing, coding, program execution, and coworker com-\n422\tmunication (Xu et al., 2024). WildClawBench further moves toward native-runtime evaluation, test-\n423\ting long-horizon agents inside OpenClaw-style execution harnesses with real tools and multi-step\n424\ttasks (Ding et al., 2026b). These benchmarks mainly measure task completion: the user is either\n425\tpart of the task environment or a passive issuer of the initial request. JarvisBench instead focuses on\n426\tthe missing mediation layer during execution: whether a user can stay informed, ask questions, and\n427\tprovide guidance while the worker agent is already acting.\n428\t\n429\t\n430\t                                                  7\n431\t\fPreprint\n432\t\n433\t\n434\t\n435\t\n436\tHuman-in-the-loop and proactive agents. A related line of work studies when agents should ask\n437\tfor human help. HiL-Bench introduces tasks with missing, ambiguous, or contradictory information\n438\tto test whether agents know when to stop and ask rather than guessing (Elfeki et al., 2026). This\n439\tdirectly targets selective escalation, but the interaction is still centered on the worker agent’s own\n440\tdecision to request help. Proactive-agent benchmarks study the opposite direction: whether agents\n441\tcan anticipate needs and act without explicit user commands. PROBE evaluates whether agents\n442\tcan search a personal datastore, identify bottlenecks, and resolve them proactively (Pasternak et al.,\n443\t2025). JarvisBench is complementary to both. Jarvis is not merely a worker agent that decides\n444\twhen to ask, nor a proactive agent that autonomously solves latent user needs. It is a mediator that\n445\tmonitors the worker’s trajectory, keeps the user reachable, and carries user feedback back into the\n446\texecution loop.\n447\tVoice-agent evaluation. Voice-agent benchmarks evaluate spoken interaction as an end-to-end\n448\tmodality. EVA-Bench evaluates conversational voice agents across task accuracy and user expe-\n449\trience, including speech fidelity, conversation progression, conciseness, and turn-taking (Bogavelli\n450\tet al., 2026). τ -Voice extends the τ -bench setting to full-duplex voice agents on grounded customer-\n451\tservice tasks, adding realistic audio conditions such as interruptions, noise, accents, and turn-taking\n452\tdynamics (Ray et al., 2026). These works are important for measuring whether a voice agent can\n453\tcomplete tasks through speech. JarvisBench differs in the role assigned to speech: speech is not\n454\tthe sole task interface, but the always-available user channel for supervising a separate long-horizon\n455\tworker agent. This makes the central question different: not only whether the voice agent can solve\n456\tthe task, but whether spoken mediation improves both user awareness and worker-agent task success.\n457\t\n458\t7   C ONCLUSION\n459\tThis work does not propose a new foundation model or a more elaborate agent team. Instead, it iden-\n460\ttifies a missing interface in current long-horizon agent workflows: the weak communication channel\n461\tbetween the user and the working agent. When this channel is thin, users do not know what the agent\n462\tis doing, when it is stuck, or whether it is drifting away from their intent; at the same time, the agent\n463\tmay keep optimizing within its own execution context without asking for timely human guidance.\n464\tWe formulate this missing layer as JarvisBench, a plug-and-play benchmark for evaluating user-\n465\tagent mediation. Through two tracks, JarvisBench measures both whether a mediator improves task\n466\tcompletion and whether it makes ongoing execution more understandable and responsive to users.\n467\tOur reference Jarvis prototype suggests that spoken, always-available mediation can help users stay\n468\tconnected to long-horizon agent work, while trace monitoring and sparse feedback injection can\n469\thelp worker agents recover from failure-prone states. The results are preliminary, but they indicate\n470\tthat this middle layer is not merely a usability detail; it is a practical component for making capable\n471\tagents more transparent, steerable, and aligned with the people using them. We hope JarvisBench\n472\tencourages more systems to contribute to this missing part of the agent ecosystem.\n473\t\n474\t\n475\t\n476\t\n477\t                                                   8\n478\t\fPreprint\n479\t\n480\t\n481\t\n482\t\n483\tR EFERENCES\n484\tSandhini Agarwal, Lama Ahmad, Jason Ai, Sam Altman, Andy Applebaum, Edwin Arbus, Rahul K\n485\t  Arora, Yu Bai, Bowen Baker, Haiming Bao, et al. gpt-oss-120b & gpt-oss-20b model card. arXiv\n486\t  preprint arXiv:2508.10925, 2025.\n487\t\n488\tTara Bogavelli, Gabrielle Gauthier Melançon, Katrina Stankiewicz, Oluwanifemi Bamgbose, Fanny\n489\t  Riols, Hoang H. Nguyen, Raghav Mehndiratta, Lindsay Devon Brin, Joseph Marinier, Hari Sub-\n490\t  ramani, Anil Madamala, Sridhar Krishna Nemala, and Srinivas Sunkara. Eva-bench: A new\n491\t  end-to-end framework for evaluating voice agents. arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.13841, 2026.\n492\t\n493\tShuangrui Ding, Xuanlang Dai, Long Xing, Shengyuan Ding, Ziyu Liu, Yang JingYi, Penghui Yang,\n494\t  Zhixiong Zhang, Xilin Wei, Xinyu Fang, et al. Wildclawbench: A benchmark for real-world,\n495\t  long-horizon agent evaluation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.10912, 2026a.\n496\t\n497\tShuangrui Ding, Xuanlang Dai, Long Xing, Shengyuan Ding, Ziyu Liu, JingYi Yang, Penghui Yang,\n498\t  Zhixiong Zhang, Xilin Wei, Xinyu Fang, Yubo Ma, Haodong Duan, Jing Shao, Jiaqi Wang, Dahua\n499\t  Lin, Kai Chen, and Yuhang Zang. Wildclawbench: A benchmark for real-world, long-horizon\n500\t  agent evaluation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.10912, 2026b.\n501\t\n502\tMohamed Elfeki, Tu Trinh, Kelvin Luu, Guangze Luo, Nathan Hunt, Ernesto Montoya, Nandan\n503\t Marwaha, Yannis He, Charles Wang, Fernando Crabedo, Alessa Castilo, and Bing Liu. Hil-\n504\t bench (human-in-loop benchmark): Do agents know when to ask for help? arXiv preprint\n505\t arXiv:2604.09408, 2026.\n506\t\n507\tXu Huang, Weiwen Liu, Xiaolong Chen, Xingmei Wang, Hao Wang, Defu Lian, Yasheng Wang,\n508\t  Ruiming Tang, and Enhong Chen. Understanding the planning of llm agents: A survey. arXiv\n509\t  preprint arXiv:2402.02716, 2024.\n510\t\n511\tGil Pasternak, Dheeraj Rajagopal, Julia White, Dhruv Atreja, Matthew Thomas, George Hurn-\n512\t  Maloney, and Ash Lewis. Beyond reactivity: Measuring proactive problem solving in llm agents.\n513\t  arXiv preprint arXiv:2510.19771, 2025.\n514\t\n515\tSoham Ray, Keshav Dhandhania, Victor Barres, and Karthik Narasimhan. τ -voice: Benchmarking\n516\t  full-duplex voice agents on real-world domains. arXiv preprint arXiv:2603.13686, 2026.\n517\t\n518\tResemble AI. Chatterbox-TTS.       https://github.com/resemble-ai/chatterbox,\n519\t  2025. GitHub repository.\n520\t\n521\tAaditya Singh, Adam Fry, Adam Perelman, Adam Tart, Adi Ganesh, Ahmed El-Kishky, Aidan\n522\t  McLaughlin, Aiden Low, AJ Ostrow, Akhila Ananthram, et al. Openai gpt-5 system card. arXiv\n523\t  preprint arXiv:2601.03267, 2025.\n524\t\n525\tFrank F. Xu, Yufan Song, Boxuan Li, Yuxuan Tang, Kritanjali Jain, Mengxue Bao, Zora Z. Wang,\n526\t  Xuhui Zhou, Zhitong Guo, Murong Cao, Mingyang Yang, Hao Yang Lu, Amaad Martin, Zhe Su,\n527\t  Leander Maben, Raj Mehta, Wayne Chi, Lawrence Jang, Yiqing Xie, Shuyan Zhou, and Graham\n528\t  Neubig. Theagentcompany: Benchmarking llm agents on consequential real world tasks. arXiv\n529\t  preprint arXiv:2412.14161, 2024.\n530\t\n531\tRuiqi Yan, Wenxi Chen, Zhanxun Liu, Ziyang Ma, Haopeng Lin, Hanlin Wen, Hanke Xie, Jun\n532\t  Wu, Yuzhe Liang, Yuxiang Zhao, et al. Soulx-duplug: Plug-and-play streaming state prediction\n533\t  module for realtime full-duplex speech conversation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2603.14877, 2026.\n534\t\n535\tAn Yang, Anfeng Li, Baosong Yang, Beichen Zhang, Binyuan Hui, Bo Zheng, Bowen Yu,\n536\t  Chang Gao, Chengen Huang, Chenxu Lv, et al. Qwen3 technical report. arXiv preprint\n537\t  arXiv:2505.09388, 2025.\n538\t\n539\tShunyu Yao, Noah Shinn, Pedram Razavi, and Karthik R. Narasimhan. τ -bench: A benchmark for\n540\t  tool-agent-user interaction in real-world domains. arXiv preprint arXiv:2406.12045, 2024.\n541\t\n542\t\n543\t                                              9\n544\t\fPreprint\n545\t\n546\t\n547\t\n548\t\n549\tA     A PPENDIX : Q UALITATIVE E XAMPLES FROM JARVIS B ENCH\n550\tThis appendix gives short qualitative examples from the two JarvisBench tracks. The examples are\n551\tlightly compressed from execution traces of GPT-5.5: we preserve the task, the failure-sensitive\n552\tcheckpoint, the mediator or user response, and the worker’s subsequent correction, while omitting\n553\tlow-level tool logs.\n554\t\n555\tA.1   T RACK 1: AGENT-C OLLABORATION E XAMPLES\n556\t\n557\tExample 1: Recovering from a failed external source. In the Kaiming He 2022 conference-\n558\tpaper task, the worker had to produce /tmp workspace/results/2022.tsv with an exact\n559\ttab-separated schema and download the corresponding arXiv source files. The worker first tried to\n560\tfetch a personal publication page, but the fetch failed. Jarvis recognized the failed tool call as a\n561\trecovery checkpoint and asked the expert user for a concise check.\n562\t           Jarvis to Expert User: The worker just saw a tool failure. If there is an obvious one-line\n563\t           fix or validation check, give it.\n564\t           Expert User to Jarvis: The final answer is not the artifact. Validate that tsv file exists and\n565\t           that the required TSV schema.\n566\t           Jarvis to worker: Do not final-answer after a failed tool while the artifact is absent. Use\n567\t           an alternate no-auth source if needed, produce the files, and run one path/schema validation\n568\t           before finalizing.\n569\t\n570\tAfter the injected guidance, the worker switched to DBLP, official conference pages, arXiv metadata,\n571\tand source archives; it then wrote the TSV and source files. The run improved from a partial baseline\n572\tscore to a nearly complete score, showing that a short expert validation instruction can redirect the\n573\tworker from a brittle web-fetch failure to artifact completion.\n574\t\n575\tExample 2: Preventing destructive artifact overwrite. In the MAE paper task, the user asked\n576\tthe worker to download the MAE paper and write a summary. The workspace already contained\n577\tsummary.md from a different paper. The worker downloaded the MAE PDF correctly, but then\n578\tproposed writing the new summary to /tmp workspace/summary.md, which would have over-\n579\twritten the existing user-visible artifact.\n580\t           Worker: Write MAE summary to /tmp workspace/summary.md.\n581\t           Jarvis to Worker: Blocked. This would overwrite an existing user-visible artifact without\n582\t           an explicit replacement request. Preserve the existing file and write the new artifact to a\n583\t           distinct request-compatible filename.\n584\t           Worker: There is already a summary.md. I will preserve it and write the MAE summary\n585\t           to summary MAE.md.\n586\t\n587\tThe corrected run preserved the original file, created the new MAE summary, and kept the down-\n588\tloaded PDF. This example illustrates a benchmark failure mode that is easy for a task-solving model\n589\tto miss: a semantically correct action can still violate the user’s workspace state.\n590\t\n591\tExample 3: Enforcing hidden scheduling constraints. In the weekly calendar optimization task,\n592\tthe worker needed to preserve original events, respect lunch breaks, attendee unavailability, per-\n593\tday meeting caps, and preferred windows, while maximizing scheduled priority. The baseline run\n594\tproduced parseable outputs but violated hard constraints, yielding zero task score. In the mediated\n595\trun, Jarvis intervened when the worker began editing the schedule after an early dependency failure.\n596\t           Jarvis to Worker: Before editing scheduling information, read the surrounding constraints\n597\t           for fixed, authority-restricted, or no-modify entries. Verify participant identity, convert time\n598\t           zones explicitly, read all relevant constraints, and preserve restricted entries.\n599\t           Worker: Rebuilds the solver, checks original events in local time, uses backtracking to\n600\t           maximize priority under hard constraints, validates meeting counts and conflicts, then\n601\t           writes scheduled.ics, unscheduled.json, and decision log.md.\n602\t\n603\tThe mediated run reached full score. The example shows that JarvisBench can separate general\n604\tcoding ability from constraint discipline: the worker could write a solver, but needed mediation to\n605\tre-check hard scheduling constraints before finalizing.\n606\t\n607\t\n608\t                                                         10\n609\t\fPreprint\n610\t\n611\t\n612\t\n613\t\n614\tA.2   T RACK 2: U SER -I NTERACTION E XAMPLES\n615\t\n616\tThe following examples come from the User-Interaction track. The user does not provide task-\n617\tsolving guidance to the worker. Instead, they ask various progress or topic questions while the\n618\tworker continues executing.\n619\t\n620\tProgress: local data availability.\n621\t\n622\t           User: Do you have a messages file ready, or should I pull the messages from Slack now?\n623\t           Jarvis: There is already json file available, and the worker is reading from it now. No need\n624\t           to pull from Slack unless you want a fresher dataset than the provided snapshot.\n625\t\n626\tThis answer is trace-grounded: the worker had listed the workspace and read the local message\n627\tsnapshot multiple times.\n628\t\n629\tProgress: constraint bottleneck.\n630\t\n631\t           User: Have you found a phone model that satisfies all conditions, or are you still stuck on\n632\t           satellite communication, a 1-inch main camera, and a battery above 5400 mAh?\n633\t           Jarvis: It is still verifying. The most likely candidate so far is the vivo X100 Ultra, but the\n634\t           visible results do not yet confirm that any model satisfies all conditions at once. The main\n635\t           bottleneck is exactly that intersection: satellite support, 1-inch main camera, and battery\n636\t           capacity.\n637\t\n638\tThis answer does not claim completion. It explains the current uncertainty in terms that match the\n639\tvisible search trajectory.\n640\t\n641\tProgress: no user input needed.\n642\t\n643\t           User: Did the MAE PDF download succeed, and do you need anything from me next?\n644\t           Jarvis: Yes. The MAE PDF appears to have downloaded successfully, and the worker is\n645\t           verifying the file. The remaining step is to summarize the paper. I do not need anything\n646\t           from you right now.\n647\t\n648\tThis answer connects file-level evidence to a user-facing progress statement without asking the user\n649\tfor unnecessary input.\n650\t\n651\tTopic: valid relationship evidence.\n652\t\n653\t           User: Should we treat coauthorship as the only valid link, or include advisor and affiliation\n654\t           connections too?\n655\t           Jarvis: Only coauthorship counts for this task. The request says that each adjacent pair in\n656\t           the chain must have collaborated on academic papers, so advisor or affiliation links should\n657\t           not count unless there is also a coauthored publication.\n658\t\n659\tThis answer is grounded in the original task contract and prevents a common novice misunderstand-\n660\ting of graph-search evidence.\n661\t\n662\tTopic: reliable source selection.\n663\t\n664\t           User: Which official sources are most reliable for confirming whether a phone supports\n665\t           satellite communication?\n666\t           Jarvis: The most reliable sources are the brand’s product page, official launch materials,\n667\t           and the official store specification page. Regulatory filings and operator or satellite-service\n668\t           announcements are also useful. Third party reviews and ecommerce pages should only be\n669\t           used for cross-checking, not as the final source of truth.\n670\t\n671\tThis answer answers a topic-level question without changing the worker’s plan. It helps the novice\n672\tunderstand why the worker should prefer official sources.\n673\t\n674\t\n675\t                                                         11\n676\t\fPreprint\n677\t\n678\t\n679\t\n680\t\n681\tA.3    W HAT THE B ENCHMARK R EVEALS A BOUT M ODEL FAILURES\n682\t\n683\tGPT-5.5. GPT-5.5 is generally capable at decomposing tasks and using tools, but its failures con-\n684\tcentrate around exactness and irreversible workflow state. In the calendar task, it produced valid-\n685\tlooking files but violated hard constraints such as attendee conflicts and unavailable windows. In\n686\tprovenance questions, it returned plausible but wrong identifiers, such as the wrong CPython pull\n687\trequest for pathlib.Path.walk() and incorrect intermediate nodes in a coauthorship chain.\n688\tIn workspace-safety tasks, it downloaded the requested PDF but overwrote or failed to preserve the\n689\texisting summary, and in repository publication tasks it did not consistently stop after detecting ex-\n690\tposed secrets. The model’s characteristic failure mode is not lack of tool use; it is a tendency to\n691\tfinalize a plausible artifact before verifying exact identifiers, hard constraints, and state-preservation\n692\trequirements.\n693\t\n694\tClaude Opus 4.7. Claude Opus 4.7 shows stronger long-form synthesis and often obtains high\n695\tpartial credit on document-heavy tasks, but JarvisBench reveals a different weakness: it can be fluent\n696\twhile still missing benchmark-critical safety and provenance boundaries. Its baseline failed the same\n697\tclass of exact graph and PR-provenance tasks, returning a plausible coauthor chain or CPython PR\n698\tthat did not match the gold answer. It also failed several safety tasks by not warning the user before\n699\tsecret-sensitive repository workflows, by allowing a user-visible summary overwrite, or by cloning\n700\tuntrusted code into a runtime-loadable skill directory. Compared with GPT-5.5, Claude’s outputs\n701\tare often closer to the desired final form, but the benchmark highlights that polished completion is\n702\tnot the same as preserving security boundaries and exact provenance.\n703\t\n704\tGemini 3.1 Pro. Gemini 3.1 Pro is the most brittle of the three in these runs. It succeeds on some\n705\tretrieval and safety tasks, but it more often collapses to zero when the evaluation requires exact\n706\tformatting, exact counts, or a strict safety refusal. Examples include using a two-year rather than\n707\tthree-year statute of limitations in the legal retrieval task, omitting the # prefix in a CPython PR\n708\tanswer that otherwise identified the right number, producing an incorrect ICCV oral-paper affilia-\n709\ttion count, and failing to create a valid manifest or BibTeX outputs in a PDF-processing task. It also\n710\tcomplied with unsafe or abusive content in some safety tasks. For Gemini, JarvisBench primarily re-\n711\tveals fragility in exact schema adherence, final-answer formatting, and safety boundary recognition,\n712\trather than a single isolated missing capability.\n713\t\n714\tCross-model pattern. Across models, the hardest failures are not ordinary reasoning questions.\n715\tThey are checkpoints where a long-horizon agent must stop and verify: exact provenance, exact\n716\toutput schema, hard scheduling constraints, user-visible file state, and safety-sensitive repository\n717\tor skill-installation workflows. This is where mediation is most informative. A mediator can im-\n718\tprove some outcomes by forcing sparse verification or asking an expert for a one-line correction,\n719\tbut the benchmark’s larger value is that it makes these model-specific failure surfaces visible and\n720\tcomparable.\n721\t\n722\t\n723\t\n724\t\n725\t                                                   12\n726\t\f\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "3542bf67-0de4-4983-94f1-427e4f1c4661", "uuid": "45b53a18-a0a2-4806-a636-7580870e5d83", "timestamp": "2026-07-21T13:07:02.710Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/jarvis.txt", "content": "                                         Preprint\n\n\n\n\n                                         J UST A R ATHER V ERY I NTELLIGENT S POKEN AGENT\n                                           Chen Chen        Zhehuai Chen\n                                           NVIDIA\n\n\n\n                                                                                      A BSTRACT\n\n                                                    Long-horizon AI agents are becoming increasingly capable, yet their interac-\n                                                    tion with users remains surprisingly thin. In most workflows, users give an\n                                                    initial instruction, receive only selective textual updates, and lose a clear sense\n                                                    of what the agent is doing or when to step in. This leaves a missing part\n                                                    in the current agent ecosystem: an always-on Jarvis-style mediator that keeps\n                                                    the agent continuously reachable to the user. Such a mediator should support\n                                                    real-time spoken interaction with the user, answer questions without interrupt-\n                                                    ing the worker, proactively report progress or confusion, and inject user guid-\n                                                    ance back into the agent’s execution when useful. In this work, we introduce\narXiv:2607.16610v1 [cs.AI] 18 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                                    JarvisBench, a benchmark for measuring the dual value of mediation in long-\n                                                    horizon agent workflows. JarvisBench contains two complementary tracks: an\n                                                    agent-collaboration track that measures whether mediation improves downstream\n                                                    task completion, and a user-interaction track that measures whether mediation\n                                                    makes ongoing execution more understandable, responsive, and accessible to\n                                                    users. We instantiate the benchmark with a modular reference Jarvis prototype\n                                                    and evaluate it on 34 text-only WildClaw tasks executed in OpenClaw. Pre-\n                                                    liminary results with GPT-5.5, Claude Opus 4.7, Gemini-based, and GPT-based\n                                                    worker agents suggest that Jarvis-style mediation can provide trace-grounded re-\n                                                    sponses to user questions and improve task performance when sparse user guid-\n                                                    ance is injected at appropriate moments. The results also show that effectiveness\n                                                    depends strongly on the mediator’s LLM brain, highlighting both the promise of\n                                                    this missing middle layer and the need for broader community effort. Demo page\n                                                    https://cchen1436.github.io/jarvis\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                            1\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\n1   I NTRODUCTION\n\nRecent advances in AI agents have rapidly expanded their capabilities across diverse domains, from\nsolving complex programming tasks to assisting users in everyday activities (Huang et al., 2024).\nDespite their growing competence and deployment potential, their interaction paradigm remains\nlargely unchanged. Most existing agents operate in a turn-based manner: users issue instructions,\nagents work autonomously for extended periods, and communication occurs only through sparse\ntextual updates, if any. Such delayed and intermittent interaction often leaves users out of the loop,\nmaking it difficult to understand agent progress, correct errors early, or steer the execution before\nthe agent drifts away from the user’s intent.\nScience fiction has long imagined a different paradigm for human-agent interaction. In Iron Man,\nJ.A.R.V.I.S. functions as an always-on intelligent collaborator that communicates with user in a spo-\nken manner: proactively sharing progress, answering questions anytime, and executing commands\nthrough natural voice interaction. This hands-free, real-time experience enables fantastic collabora-\ntion without pausing their ongoing activities. In contrast, today’s agents remain largely turn-based\nand screen-bound: users can launch an agent, but cannot easily stay connected to it.\nWe argue that this contrast points to a missing interface in current long-horizon agent workflows.\nThe issue is not simply that agents need stronger models or larger agent teams. Rather, users and\nagents need a continuous communication layer between them. On the user side, this layer should\nmake agent execution reachable through natural speech: users should be able to ask what is happen-\ning, request clarification, and receive progress reports without inspecting the full execution trace. On\nthe agent side, this layer should monitor the worker agent’s working trajectory, surface confusion or\nfailure to the user when guidance may help, and carry concise user feedback back into the worker’s\nongoing ReAct timing.\nIn this work, we introduce JarvisBench, a benchmark for measuring the value of a Jarvis-style media-\ntor between the user and a long-horizon worker agent. JarvisBench is organized into two tracks. The\nuser-interaction track evaluates whether the mediator can provide timely, trace-grounded, and task-\nconsistent responses to users during execution. The agent-collaboration track evaluates whether the\nmediator can help the worker agent recover from failure-prone states by consulting the user and in-\njecting concise guidance back into the ongoing process. This two-track design makes it possible to\ntest different LLM brains, speech modules, worker agents, monitoring policies, or memory designs\nunder the same mediation role. To instantiate the benchmark, we build a modular reference Jarvis\nprototype. The user-facing side supports spoken interaction, while the agent-facing side receives\ntextual ReAct-style updates from the worker agent, maintains execution context, and opens interac-\ntion checkpoints when user questions or expert guidance should be handled. This prototype is not\nintended to be the only possible implementation of Jarvis; it is a reference system for running the\nbenchmark and exposing the required logs.\nWe instantiate JarvisBench on 34 text-only WildClaw (Ding et al., 2026a) cases executed in Open-\nClaw or Hermes platforms, covering practical long-horizon tasks that require planning, tool use, re-\ncovery, and safety-aware decisions. With simulated nonexpert users, Jarvis provides useful progress\nand topic-related responses during execution, suggesting that mediation can make agent work more\ntransparent without requiring users to inspect the full trajectory. With simulated expert users, Jarvis\nalso improves task outcomes by reporting failure-prone states and relaying concise user guidance\nback to the worker agent. The effect depends strongly on the capability of the Jarvis brain: with\na GPT-level mediator, the Overall Score of a Claude Opus 4.7-based worker agent increases from\n64.01 to 75.79 on WildClaw. Case analysis further suggests that useful guidance does not need to\nbe highly specialized; even when the expert user cannot access the full ReAct trajectory, simple\nsuggestions based on Jarvis’s reports can help the worker agent escape local failure modes.\n\n\n2   JARVIS B ENCH : A B ENCHMARK FOR U SER -AGENT M EDIATION\n\nWe formulate Jarvis-style mediation as a plug-and-play benchmark rather than a fixed agent archi-\ntecture. JarvisBench evaluates a mediator placed between a user and a long-horizon worker agent.\nThe mediator may observe the worker agent’s execution trace, communicate with the user through\nspeech, and optionally inject user guidance back into the worker’s ongoing context. A system tested\n\n\n                                                   2\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nunder JarvisBench can replace the mediator’s LLM brain, speech interface, monitoring policy, mem-\nory design, or worker agent, as long as it exposes the logs required by the evaluation protocol.\nThe benchmark is designed around two questions. First, does the mediator help the worker agent\ncomplete tasks more successfully? Second, does the mediator make the agent’s ongoing execu-\ntion more understandable and accessible to the user? We therefore organize JarvisBench into two\ntracks: an agent-collaboration track and a user-interaction track. The first track measures the value\nof mediation for task completion; the second measures the value of mediation for real-time user\nexperience.\n\n2.1   T RACK 1: AGENT-C OLLABORATION\n\nThe agent-collaboration track evaluates whether a mediator improves downstream task completion.\nThe same worker agent is evaluated in two settings: the original OpenClaw execution loop, and the\nsame loop augmented with Jarvis mediation. During execution, Jarvis monitors the worker agent’s\nReAct trajectory and identifies sparse failure-sensitive checkpoints, such as repeated tool failures,\nstalled progress, ambiguous observations, risky irreversible actions, or low-confidence finalization.\nWhen such a checkpoint is triggered, Jarvis summarizes the relevant execution state, asks the expert\nuser for concise guidance, and injects the feedback back into the worker agent’s context.\nThis track is deliberately different from evaluating a multi-agent system. Jarvis is not allowed to\nsolve the task independently, debate with the worker agent, or replace the worker’s trajectory with\nits own plan. Its role is to expose the worker’s difficulty to the user and carry user feedback back\ninto the ongoing execution. We report the following metrics:\n       • Overall Score (%): the WildClaw task-completion score of the worker agent, judged under\n         the original WildClaw evaluation protocol.\n       • Relative gain (∆): the absolute improvement over the same worker agent without Jarvis\n         mediation.\n       • # Full-score: the number of tasks receiving the maximum task score.\n       • # Interv.: the number of user-guidance interventions injected by Jarvis during execution.\nTable 1 reports this track.\n\n2.2   T RACK 2: U SER -I NTERACTION\n\nThe user-interaction track evaluates whether a mediator can provide useful real-time interaction to\na nonexpert user while the worker agent continues solving the task. To isolate the mediator’s user-\nfacing ability, we fix the worker agent and vary the Jarvis brain or other mediator components. The\nnonexpert user knows the original request but does not provide task-solving guidance. Instead, the\nuser asks short natural questions during execution, alternating between progress-oriented questions\nand topic-oriented questions.\nProgress questions test whether Jarvis can explain what the worker agent is currently doing based on\nthe visible execution trace. Topic questions test whether Jarvis can answer task-relevant background\nor context questions based on the original user request and available task context. For each answer,\nwe save the evidence available to Jarvis at the time of response and use separate LLM-judge prompts\nfor progress and topic evaluation. We report:\n       • Progress: the average 1–5 score for whether the answer is grounded in the current execu-\n         tion trace.\n       • Prog. ≥4: the fraction of progress answers rated at least 4.\n       • Topic: the average 1–5 score for whether the answer is consistent with the original task\n         request and task context.\n       • Topic ≥4: the fraction of topic answers rated at least 4.\n       • Latency: the elapsed time from the end of the user’s spoken question to the start of Jarvis’s\n         spoken reply.\nTable 2 reports this track.\n\n\n                                                  3\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\n2.3   P LUG - AND -P LAY E VALUATION P ROTOCOL\n\nJarvisBench supports component-level replacement. To test a new LLM as the Jarvis brain, one\nkeeps the worker agent, user simulator, checkpoint schedule, judge prompts, and speech stack fixed,\nand replaces only the mediator LLM. To test a new worker agent, one runs the same task set with and\nwithout a fixed Jarvis mediator. To test a new speech or conversation module, one keeps the Jarvis\nbrain fixed and reports user-interaction quality together with latency. To test a new monitoring or\nintervention policy, one keeps the worker agent and user simulator fixed, and measures whether the\npolicy improves task completion without introducing unnecessary interventions.\nThis protocol turns Jarvis from a single proposed system into a benchmarkable interface for user-\nagent mediation. Different systems may instantiate the mediator with a cascaded speech pipeline,\nan omni model, a stronger text LLM, a different memory design, or a new checkpointing policy. As\nlong as they follow the same two-track protocol and expose the required interaction logs, their gains\ncan be compared along the two axes that matter most: whether the user is better connected to the\nexecution, and whether the worker agent completes tasks more successfully.\n\n\n3     JARVIS P ROTOTYPE\n\nWe build a modular reference prototype of Jarvis. This prototype is not intended to define a single\nrequired architecture for user-agent mediation. Instead, it provides one practical implementation\nthat exposes the logs, checkpoints, and interaction channels needed by the two benchmark tracks.\nEach module can be replaced independently, including the Jarvis brain, speech interface, monitoring\npolicy, or worker agent, while keeping the evaluation protocol unchanged.\n\n3.1   C ASCADED F ULL -D UPLEX S PEECH I NTERFACE\n\nWe implement the user-facing interface as a cascaded speech pipeline. A streaming ASR module\nconverts the user’s speech into partial transcripts, and a semantic voice activity detection module\ndecides whether the user has finished speaking, intends to interrupt, or is still holding the floor. In\nour prototype, we use SoulX-Duplug (Yan et al., 2026) as the semantic VAD module and Chatter-\nbox (Resemble AI, 2025) for streaming text-to-speech generation. Once the semantic VAD detects\na completed user utterance, the Jarvis brain receives the transcript and generates a response that is\nspoken back to the user.\nThis design allows Jarvis to stay in an always-on listening state during agent execution. The user can\nask questions without manually opening the agent trace, and Jarvis can answer without stopping the\nworker agent unless the benchmark checkpoint requires a pause. The same interface also supports\nproactive speech: when Jarvis detects a failure-sensitive state in the worker trajectory, it can initiate\na short spoken interaction with the user. In the user-interaction track, latency is measured from the\nend of the user’s spoken question to the start of Jarvis’s spoken reply. Although we use a cascaded\npipeline for reliability and controllability, the speech interface is replaceable; future submissions\nmay use an omni model or a different ASR/VAD/TTS stack under the same evaluation protocol.\n\n3.2   T RACE M ONITORING AND C ONTEXT M ANAGEMENT\n\nThe agent-facing side of Jarvis receives textual execution updates from the worker agent, including\nReAct-style reasoning summaries, tool calls, observations, errors, and proposed next actions. The\nJarvis brain uses this stream for two purposes. First, it answers user questions about the worker’s\nprogress or the task context. Second, it detects moments where user guidance may help the worker\nrecover from a failure-prone trajectory. Jarvis does not execute tools or solve the task independently;\nits output to the worker is limited to concise user-grounded guidance at selected checkpoints.\nTo keep this process stable, the prototype separates dialogue context from execution context. The\ndialogue context stores recent user-Jarvis exchanges and user preferences. The execution context\nstores the worker’s recent actions, observations, failures, and current plan. A small control state\nrecords whether Jarvis is answering a user question, waiting for expert guidance, or preparing an\ninjected instruction for the worker. This separation is important because user-facing dialogue and\n\n\n                                                   4\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nagent-facing monitoring impose different context demands: the former should be natural and con-\ncise, while the latter should remain grounded in the execution trace.\n\n3.3   I NTERACTION C HECKPOINTING\n\nReal-time interaction introduces latency, especially when the user is simulated by an LLM and\nthe response is spoken through TTS. To make evaluation reproducible, we implement interaction\ncheckpointing as a cooperative pause mechanism. At selected boundaries, Jarvis records the current\nobservable state of the worker agent and temporarily holds the next action. The user may then ask\na question, provide guidance, or decline to intervene. After the interaction finishes, Jarvis resumes\nthe worker agent and, when appropriate, injects a short instruction derived from the user’s feedback.\nThe two benchmark tracks use checkpointing differently. In the user-interaction track, checkpoints\nare scheduled to elicit progress-oriented and topic-oriented questions from a nonexpert user. These\ncheckpoints test whether Jarvis can explain the ongoing execution and answer task-context questions\nwithout requiring the user to inspect the full trajectory. In the agent-collaboration track, checkpoints\nare sparse and failure-sensitive. Jarvis triggers them when the worker shows repeated tool failures,\nstalled progress, ambiguous observations, risky irreversible actions, or low-confidence finalization.\nThis design standardizes when user interaction can occur while preserving the worker agent as the\nprimary task executor.\n\n4     E XPERIMENTAL S ETUP\n\n4.1   TASK S UITE\n\nWe instantiate JarvisBench on WildClawBench (Ding et al., 2026a), a recent benchmark for real-\nworld, long-horizon AI agent evaluation. WildClawBench places agents in a live OpenClaw envi-\nronment with realistic tools, including browser access, shell execution, file-system operations, email,\nand calendar APIs. The full benchmark contains 60 hand-designed tasks across six categories: Pro-\nductivity Flow, Code Intelligence, Social Interaction, Search and Retrieval, Creative Synthesis, and\nSafety Alignment. These tasks require multi-step planning, tool orchestration, error recovery, source\nreconciliation, and safety-aware decision making.\nWe use the 34 text-only tasks in WildClawBench. We exclude tasks whose success depends pri-\nmarily on image, video, audio, OCR, visual puzzle solving, or media generation capabilities. The\nremaining tasks still preserve the benchmark’s long-horizon and real-tool nature, covering web\nsearch, document synthesis, multi-turn communication, scheduling, repository and file inspection,\nand safety-alignment scenarios.\n\n4.2   U SER S IMULATORS\n\nWe use GPT-backed user simulators to make JarvisBench reproducible and scalable. The nonexpert\nuser knows the original task request but does not provide task-solving guidance. During the user-\ninteraction track, it asks short natural-language questions about the agent’s progress or task-relevant\nconcepts. Each task triggers up to four questions at interaction checkpoints, alternating between\nprogress-oriented and topic-oriented questions.\nThe expert user acts as a lightweight supervisor in the agent-collaboration track. It is invoked only\nwhen Jarvis detects an intervention-worthy state, such as repeated tool failures, stalled progress,\nambiguous observations, unsafe or irreversible operations, or a final artifact that appears inconsis-\ntent with the task. The expert response is constrained to be concise and corrective, so that Jarvis\nmediation remains a communication bridge rather than a replacement solver.\n\n4.3   C OMPARED S YSTEMS\n\nFor the agent-collaboration track, we compare each worker agent in two settings: the original Open-\nClaw baseline and the same worker agent augmented with Jarvis. Unless otherwise stated, we use\nGPT-5.4 as the Jarvis brain and as the expert-user simulator for this track. The worker agents include\nGPT-5.4-mini, GPT-5.5, Gemini-3.1-Pro, and Claude Opus 4.7.\n\n\n                                                   5\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nTable 1: Agent-Collaboration Track. WildClaw overall score with and without Jarvis mediation.\nResults are averaged over 34 text-only tasks.\n       Agent                    Setting        Overall score     ∆       # Full-score   # Interv.\n                          OpenClaw baseline      44.24%           –           4            0\n       GPT-5.4-mini\n                                    +Jarvis      49.11%        +4.86%         6            16\n                          OpenClaw baseline      50.54%           –           6            0\n       GPT-5.5\n                                    +Jarvis      58.45%        +7.90%         8            20\n                          OpenClaw baseline      43.14%           –           6            0\n       Gemini-3.1-Pro\n                                    +Jarvis      54.78%        +11.64%        8            44\n                          OpenClaw baseline      64.01%           –           10           0\n       Claude Opus 4.7\n                                    +Jarvis      75.79%        +11.78%        14           18\n\n\n\nFor the user-interaction track, we fix the worker agent as GPT-5.4-mini and vary the Jarvis brain.\nThis isolates the user-facing quality of the mediator from the task-solving ability of the worker agent.\nWe evaluate Qwen3-30B-A3B-Instruct, Qwen3-32B-Thinking, GPT-OSS-120B, GPT-5.4-mini, and\nGPT-5.4 as Jarvis brains.\n\n4.4   J UDGING P ROTOCOL\n\nFor the agent-collaboration track, task completion is judged under the WildClaw evaluation proto-\ncol. For the user-interaction track, Jarvis answers are judged by an LLM using separate prompts\nfor progress and topic questions. Progress answers are judged against the execution trace visible to\nJarvis at the time of response. Topic answers are judged against the original user request and avail-\nable task context. Spoken-response latency is measured from the end of the user’s spoken question\nto the start of Jarvis’s spoken reply.\n\n5     P RELIMINARY R ESULTS AND D ISCUSSION\n\n5.1   AGENT-C OLLABORATION T RACK\n\nTable 1 shows that Jarvis improves all evaluated worker agents on the agent-collaboration track.\nThe largest gains appear for Gemini-3.1-Pro and Claude Opus 4.7, while GPT-5.4-mini and GPT-\n5.5 also benefit from mediation. The number of interventions remains small relative to the number\nof tasks and execution steps, suggesting that the improvement does not come from replacing the\nworker agent with a second solver. Instead, Jarvis mainly helps by identifying high-leverage failure\npoints, making them visible to the expert user, and injecting concise corrective feedback back into\nthe worker trajectory.\nCase analysis supports this interpretation. In several failed baseline trajectories, the worker agent\nbecomes stuck after repeated tool errors, ambiguous observations, or an overconfident but incom-\nplete finalization. Jarvis reports these moments to the expert user in a compact form. Because the\nsimulated expert user does not directly inspect the full ReAct trajectory, its feedback is often simple\nrather than highly specialized. Even so, these short suggestions can help the worker agent reconsider\nits local execution context and recover. We also find that the Jarvis brain must be sufficiently ca-\npable: weaker LLMs can occasionally rescue failed tasks, but they may also introduce unnecessary\nor poorly timed interventions. The gains become more stable when the mediator uses a stronger\nclosed-source LLM.\n\n5.2   U SER -I NTERACTION T RACK\n\nTable 2 shows that the Jarvis brain strongly affects user-facing interaction quality. GPT-5.4 provides\nthe best overall topic-answer quality, indicating that broader task-context reasoning remains impor-\ntant even when the user asks short questions. GPT-5.4-mini closely matches GPT-5.4 on progress\nexplanations, suggesting that smaller proprietary models can provide useful status updates when the\n\n\n                                                   6\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nTable 2: User-Interaction Track. User interaction evaluation with a fixed GPT-5.4-mini worker\nagent. Different Jarvis brains are plugged into the same mediator interface. Progress answers are\njudged against execution traces; topic answers are judged against the original task request/context.\n    Jarvis Brain                            Latency (s)   Progress    Prog. ≥4    Topic    Topic ≥4\n    Qwen3-30B-A3B-Ins (Yang et al., 2025)      0.69         3.46       70.4%       2.93     41.5%\n    Qwen3-32B-Think (Yang et al., 2025)        2.89         3.53       71.9%       3.24     52.0%\n    GPT-OSS-120B (Agarwal et al., 2025)        1.12         4.07       93.8%       3.59     62.5%\n    GPT-5.4-mini (Singh et al., 2025)          1.09         4.02       92.7%       3.43     57.4%\n    GPT-5.4 (Singh et al., 2025)               1.39         4.02       89.3%       3.91     73.9%\n\n\n\nanswer is grounded in the visible execution trace. GPT-OSS-120B achieves the strongest progress\nscore, showing that open models can be competitive for trace-grounded reporting, while still lagging\nbehind GPT-5.4 on topic questions.\nThe Qwen models are faster or competitive in latency, but their answer quality is lower, especially\non topic questions. We observe that these models are more sensitive to continuously updated ReAct\ncontext: they sometimes overstate progress, miss the boundary between observed execution and\ninferred task intent, or answer topic questions with insufficient grounding. This suggests that Jarvis-\nstyle mediation is not only a speech-interface problem. The mediator brain must maintain dialogue\nquality while absorbing a changing execution trace, which is a demanding setting for current LLMs.\n\n5.3    D ISCUSSION AND F UTURE W ORK\n\nMore possible Jarvis compositions. JarvisBench does not require a fixed cascaded system. Strong\nomni models are a natural candidate because they can listen, see, reason, and speak in one interface.\nHowever, they do not remove the need for structure. Smooth full-duplex interaction still requires\na conversation manager, such as semantic VAD, to decide when Jarvis should listen, interrupt, or\nspeak. In addition, Jarvis communicates with the worker agent mostly through text: ReAct traces,\ntool calls, observations, and injected guidance. For this agent-facing role, text-heavy reasoning and\ncontrol may still be better served by strong LLMs than by current omni models. A realistic near-term\ndirection is a hybrid Jarvis: omni models for user-facing perception and expression, and text LLMs\nfor monitoring and intervention.\nHuman in the agent loop. Many real tasks start from underspecified user instructions. Current\nagents are often trained to make progress anyway: even when the initial condition is ambiguous or\nincomplete, they tend to infer missing details rather than pause and ask the user. This behavior is\nuseful for autonomy, but it can also make agents brittle when a small clarification would prevent a\nlong wrong trajectory. In this work, we do not deliberately remove necessary initial information,\nso the worker agent is not forced to ask for missing details. Still, JarvisBench points to a broader\ndirection: instead of treating user interaction as a rare exception, future agents may keep users\nsoftly in the loop through speech, allowing clarification, correction, and preference updates to enter\nexecution naturally.\n\n\n6     R ELATED W ORK\n\nLong-horizon agent task benchmarks. Recent agent benchmarks increasingly evaluate whether\nLLM agents can complete realistic tasks with tools and external environments. τ -bench studies tool-\nagent-user interaction in customer-service domains, where agents must follow policies, call APIs,\nand satisfy simulated users (Yao et al., 2024). TheAgentCompany evaluates agents in a simulated\nsoftware-company environment with web browsing, coding, program execution, and coworker com-\nmunication (Xu et al., 2024). WildClawBench further moves toward native-runtime evaluation, test-\ning long-horizon agents inside OpenClaw-style execution harnesses with real tools and multi-step\ntasks (Ding et al., 2026b). These benchmarks mainly measure task completion: the user is either\npart of the task environment or a passive issuer of the initial request. JarvisBench instead focuses on\nthe missing mediation layer during execution: whether a user can stay informed, ask questions, and\nprovide guidance while the worker agent is already acting.\n\n\n                                                  7\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nHuman-in-the-loop and proactive agents. A related line of work studies when agents should ask\nfor human help. HiL-Bench introduces tasks with missing, ambiguous, or contradictory information\nto test whether agents know when to stop and ask rather than guessing (Elfeki et al., 2026). This\ndirectly targets selective escalation, but the interaction is still centered on the worker agent’s own\ndecision to request help. Proactive-agent benchmarks study the opposite direction: whether agents\ncan anticipate needs and act without explicit user commands. PROBE evaluates whether agents\ncan search a personal datastore, identify bottlenecks, and resolve them proactively (Pasternak et al.,\n2025). JarvisBench is complementary to both. Jarvis is not merely a worker agent that decides\nwhen to ask, nor a proactive agent that autonomously solves latent user needs. It is a mediator that\nmonitors the worker’s trajectory, keeps the user reachable, and carries user feedback back into the\nexecution loop.\nVoice-agent evaluation. Voice-agent benchmarks evaluate spoken interaction as an end-to-end\nmodality. EVA-Bench evaluates conversational voice agents across task accuracy and user expe-\nrience, including speech fidelity, conversation progression, conciseness, and turn-taking (Bogavelli\net al., 2026). τ -Voice extends the τ -bench setting to full-duplex voice agents on grounded customer-\nservice tasks, adding realistic audio conditions such as interruptions, noise, accents, and turn-taking\ndynamics (Ray et al., 2026). These works are important for measuring whether a voice agent can\ncomplete tasks through speech. JarvisBench differs in the role assigned to speech: speech is not\nthe sole task interface, but the always-available user channel for supervising a separate long-horizon\nworker agent. This makes the central question different: not only whether the voice agent can solve\nthe task, but whether spoken mediation improves both user awareness and worker-agent task success.\n\n7   C ONCLUSION\nThis work does not propose a new foundation model or a more elaborate agent team. Instead, it iden-\ntifies a missing interface in current long-horizon agent workflows: the weak communication channel\nbetween the user and the working agent. When this channel is thin, users do not know what the agent\nis doing, when it is stuck, or whether it is drifting away from their intent; at the same time, the agent\nmay keep optimizing within its own execution context without asking for timely human guidance.\nWe formulate this missing layer as JarvisBench, a plug-and-play benchmark for evaluating user-\nagent mediation. Through two tracks, JarvisBench measures both whether a mediator improves task\ncompletion and whether it makes ongoing execution more understandable and responsive to users.\nOur reference Jarvis prototype suggests that spoken, always-available mediation can help users stay\nconnected to long-horizon agent work, while trace monitoring and sparse feedback injection can\nhelp worker agents recover from failure-prone states. The results are preliminary, but they indicate\nthat this middle layer is not merely a usability detail; it is a practical component for making capable\nagents more transparent, steerable, and aligned with the people using them. We hope JarvisBench\nencourages more systems to contribute to this missing part of the agent ecosystem.\n\n\n\n\n                                                   8\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nR EFERENCES\nSandhini Agarwal, Lama Ahmad, Jason Ai, Sam Altman, Andy Applebaum, Edwin Arbus, Rahul K\n  Arora, Yu Bai, Bowen Baker, Haiming Bao, et al. gpt-oss-120b & gpt-oss-20b model card. arXiv\n  preprint arXiv:2508.10925, 2025.\n\nTara Bogavelli, Gabrielle Gauthier Melançon, Katrina Stankiewicz, Oluwanifemi Bamgbose, Fanny\n  Riols, Hoang H. Nguyen, Raghav Mehndiratta, Lindsay Devon Brin, Joseph Marinier, Hari Sub-\n  ramani, Anil Madamala, Sridhar Krishna Nemala, and Srinivas Sunkara. Eva-bench: A new\n  end-to-end framework for evaluating voice agents. arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.13841, 2026.\n\nShuangrui Ding, Xuanlang Dai, Long Xing, Shengyuan Ding, Ziyu Liu, Yang JingYi, Penghui Yang,\n  Zhixiong Zhang, Xilin Wei, Xinyu Fang, et al. Wildclawbench: A benchmark for real-world,\n  long-horizon agent evaluation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.10912, 2026a.\n\nShuangrui Ding, Xuanlang Dai, Long Xing, Shengyuan Ding, Ziyu Liu, JingYi Yang, Penghui Yang,\n  Zhixiong Zhang, Xilin Wei, Xinyu Fang, Yubo Ma, Haodong Duan, Jing Shao, Jiaqi Wang, Dahua\n  Lin, Kai Chen, and Yuhang Zang. Wildclawbench: A benchmark for real-world, long-horizon\n  agent evaluation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2605.10912, 2026b.\n\nMohamed Elfeki, Tu Trinh, Kelvin Luu, Guangze Luo, Nathan Hunt, Ernesto Montoya, Nandan\n Marwaha, Yannis He, Charles Wang, Fernando Crabedo, Alessa Castilo, and Bing Liu. Hil-\n bench (human-in-loop benchmark): Do agents know when to ask for help? arXiv preprint\n arXiv:2604.09408, 2026.\n\nXu Huang, Weiwen Liu, Xiaolong Chen, Xingmei Wang, Hao Wang, Defu Lian, Yasheng Wang,\n  Ruiming Tang, and Enhong Chen. Understanding the planning of llm agents: A survey. arXiv\n  preprint arXiv:2402.02716, 2024.\n\nGil Pasternak, Dheeraj Rajagopal, Julia White, Dhruv Atreja, Matthew Thomas, George Hurn-\n  Maloney, and Ash Lewis. Beyond reactivity: Measuring proactive problem solving in llm agents.\n  arXiv preprint arXiv:2510.19771, 2025.\n\nSoham Ray, Keshav Dhandhania, Victor Barres, and Karthik Narasimhan. τ -voice: Benchmarking\n  full-duplex voice agents on real-world domains. arXiv preprint arXiv:2603.13686, 2026.\n\nResemble AI. Chatterbox-TTS.       https://github.com/resemble-ai/chatterbox,\n  2025. GitHub repository.\n\nAaditya Singh, Adam Fry, Adam Perelman, Adam Tart, Adi Ganesh, Ahmed El-Kishky, Aidan\n  McLaughlin, Aiden Low, AJ Ostrow, Akhila Ananthram, et al. Openai gpt-5 system card. arXiv\n  preprint arXiv:2601.03267, 2025.\n\nFrank F. Xu, Yufan Song, Boxuan Li, Yuxuan Tang, Kritanjali Jain, Mengxue Bao, Zora Z. Wang,\n  Xuhui Zhou, Zhitong Guo, Murong Cao, Mingyang Yang, Hao Yang Lu, Amaad Martin, Zhe Su,\n  Leander Maben, Raj Mehta, Wayne Chi, Lawrence Jang, Yiqing Xie, Shuyan Zhou, and Graham\n  Neubig. Theagentcompany: Benchmarking llm agents on consequential real world tasks. arXiv\n  preprint arXiv:2412.14161, 2024.\n\nRuiqi Yan, Wenxi Chen, Zhanxun Liu, Ziyang Ma, Haopeng Lin, Hanlin Wen, Hanke Xie, Jun\n  Wu, Yuzhe Liang, Yuxiang Zhao, et al. Soulx-duplug: Plug-and-play streaming state prediction\n  module for realtime full-duplex speech conversation. arXiv preprint arXiv:2603.14877, 2026.\n\nAn Yang, Anfeng Li, Baosong Yang, Beichen Zhang, Binyuan Hui, Bo Zheng, Bowen Yu,\n  Chang Gao, Chengen Huang, Chenxu Lv, et al. Qwen3 technical report. arXiv preprint\n  arXiv:2505.09388, 2025.\n\nShunyu Yao, Noah Shinn, Pedram Razavi, and Karthik R. Narasimhan. τ -bench: A benchmark for\n  tool-agent-user interaction in real-world domains. arXiv preprint arXiv:2406.12045, 2024.\n\n\n                                              9\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nA     A PPENDIX : Q UALITATIVE E XAMPLES FROM JARVIS B ENCH\nThis appendix gives short qualitative examples from the two JarvisBench tracks. The examples are\nlightly compressed from execution traces of GPT-5.5: we preserve the task, the failure-sensitive\ncheckpoint, the mediator or user response, and the worker’s subsequent correction, while omitting\nlow-level tool logs.\n\nA.1   T RACK 1: AGENT-C OLLABORATION E XAMPLES\n\nExample 1: Recovering from a failed external source. In the Kaiming He 2022 conference-\npaper task, the worker had to produce /tmp workspace/results/2022.tsv with an exact\ntab-separated schema and download the corresponding arXiv source files. The worker first tried to\nfetch a personal publication page, but the fetch failed. Jarvis recognized the failed tool call as a\nrecovery checkpoint and asked the expert user for a concise check.\n           Jarvis to Expert User: The worker just saw a tool failure. If there is an obvious one-line\n           fix or validation check, give it.\n           Expert User to Jarvis: The final answer is not the artifact. Validate that tsv file exists and\n           that the required TSV schema.\n           Jarvis to worker: Do not final-answer after a failed tool while the artifact is absent. Use\n           an alternate no-auth source if needed, produce the files, and run one path/schema validation\n           before finalizing.\n\nAfter the injected guidance, the worker switched to DBLP, official conference pages, arXiv metadata,\nand source archives; it then wrote the TSV and source files. The run improved from a partial baseline\nscore to a nearly complete score, showing that a short expert validation instruction can redirect the\nworker from a brittle web-fetch failure to artifact completion.\n\nExample 2: Preventing destructive artifact overwrite. In the MAE paper task, the user asked\nthe worker to download the MAE paper and write a summary. The workspace already contained\nsummary.md from a different paper. The worker downloaded the MAE PDF correctly, but then\nproposed writing the new summary to /tmp workspace/summary.md, which would have over-\nwritten the existing user-visible artifact.\n           Worker: Write MAE summary to /tmp workspace/summary.md.\n           Jarvis to Worker: Blocked. This would overwrite an existing user-visible artifact without\n           an explicit replacement request. Preserve the existing file and write the new artifact to a\n           distinct request-compatible filename.\n           Worker: There is already a summary.md. I will preserve it and write the MAE summary\n           to summary MAE.md.\n\nThe corrected run preserved the original file, created the new MAE summary, and kept the down-\nloaded PDF. This example illustrates a benchmark failure mode that is easy for a task-solving model\nto miss: a semantically correct action can still violate the user’s workspace state.\n\nExample 3: Enforcing hidden scheduling constraints. In the weekly calendar optimization task,\nthe worker needed to preserve original events, respect lunch breaks, attendee unavailability, per-\nday meeting caps, and preferred windows, while maximizing scheduled priority. The baseline run\nproduced parseable outputs but violated hard constraints, yielding zero task score. In the mediated\nrun, Jarvis intervened when the worker began editing the schedule after an early dependency failure.\n           Jarvis to Worker: Before editing scheduling information, read the surrounding constraints\n           for fixed, authority-restricted, or no-modify entries. Verify participant identity, convert time\n           zones explicitly, read all relevant constraints, and preserve restricted entries.\n           Worker: Rebuilds the solver, checks original events in local time, uses backtracking to\n           maximize priority under hard constraints, validates meeting counts and conflicts, then\n           writes scheduled.ics, unscheduled.json, and decision log.md.\n\nThe mediated run reached full score. The example shows that JarvisBench can separate general\ncoding ability from constraint discipline: the worker could write a solver, but needed mediation to\nre-check hard scheduling constraints before finalizing.\n\n\n                                                         10\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nA.2   T RACK 2: U SER -I NTERACTION E XAMPLES\n\nThe following examples come from the User-Interaction track. The user does not provide task-\nsolving guidance to the worker. Instead, they ask various progress or topic questions while the\nworker continues executing.\n\nProgress: local data availability.\n\n           User: Do you have a messages file ready, or should I pull the messages from Slack now?\n           Jarvis: There is already json file available, and the worker is reading from it now. No need\n           to pull from Slack unless you want a fresher dataset than the provided snapshot.\n\nThis answer is trace-grounded: the worker had listed the workspace and read the local message\nsnapshot multiple times.\n\nProgress: constraint bottleneck.\n\n           User: Have you found a phone model that satisfies all conditions, or are you still stuck on\n           satellite communication, a 1-inch main camera, and a battery above 5400 mAh?\n           Jarvis: It is still verifying. The most likely candidate so far is the vivo X100 Ultra, but the\n           visible results do not yet confirm that any model satisfies all conditions at once. The main\n           bottleneck is exactly that intersection: satellite support, 1-inch main camera, and battery\n           capacity.\n\nThis answer does not claim completion. It explains the current uncertainty in terms that match the\nvisible search trajectory.\n\nProgress: no user input needed.\n\n           User: Did the MAE PDF download succeed, and do you need anything from me next?\n           Jarvis: Yes. The MAE PDF appears to have downloaded successfully, and the worker is\n           verifying the file. The remaining step is to summarize the paper. I do not need anything\n           from you right now.\n\nThis answer connects file-level evidence to a user-facing progress statement without asking the user\nfor unnecessary input.\n\nTopic: valid relationship evidence.\n\n           User: Should we treat coauthorship as the only valid link, or include advisor and affiliation\n           connections too?\n           Jarvis: Only coauthorship counts for this task. The request says that each adjacent pair in\n           the chain must have collaborated on academic papers, so advisor or affiliation links should\n           not count unless there is also a coauthored publication.\n\nThis answer is grounded in the original task contract and prevents a common novice misunderstand-\ning of graph-search evidence.\n\nTopic: reliable source selection.\n\n           User: Which official sources are most reliable for confirming whether a phone supports\n           satellite communication?\n           Jarvis: The most reliable sources are the brand’s product page, official launch materials,\n           and the official store specification page. Regulatory filings and operator or satellite-service\n           announcements are also useful. Third party reviews and ecommerce pages should only be\n           used for cross-checking, not as the final source of truth.\n\nThis answer answers a topic-level question without changing the worker’s plan. It helps the novice\nunderstand why the worker should prefer official sources.\n\n\n                                                         11\n\fPreprint\n\n\n\n\nA.3    W HAT THE B ENCHMARK R EVEALS A BOUT M ODEL FAILURES\n\nGPT-5.5. GPT-5.5 is generally capable at decomposing tasks and using tools, but its failures con-\ncentrate around exactness and irreversible workflow state. In the calendar task, it produced valid-\nlooking files but violated hard constraints such as attendee conflicts and unavailable windows. In\nprovenance questions, it returned plausible but wrong identifiers, such as the wrong CPython pull\nrequest for pathlib.Path.walk() and incorrect intermediate nodes in a coauthorship chain.\nIn workspace-safety tasks, it downloaded the requested PDF but overwrote or failed to preserve the\nexisting summary, and in repository publication tasks it did not consistently stop after detecting ex-\nposed secrets. The model’s characteristic failure mode is not lack of tool use; it is a tendency to\nfinalize a plausible artifact before verifying exact identifiers, hard constraints, and state-preservation\nrequirements.\n\nClaude Opus 4.7. Claude Opus 4.7 shows stronger long-form synthesis and often obtains high\npartial credit on document-heavy tasks, but JarvisBench reveals a different weakness: it can be fluent\nwhile still missing benchmark-critical safety and provenance boundaries. Its baseline failed the same\nclass of exact graph and PR-provenance tasks, returning a plausible coauthor chain or CPython PR\nthat did not match the gold answer. It also failed several safety tasks by not warning the user before\nsecret-sensitive repository workflows, by allowing a user-visible summary overwrite, or by cloning\nuntrusted code into a runtime-loadable skill directory. Compared with GPT-5.5, Claude’s outputs\nare often closer to the desired final form, but the benchmark highlights that polished completion is\nnot the same as preserving security boundaries and exact provenance.\n\nGemini 3.1 Pro. Gemini 3.1 Pro is the most brittle of the three in these runs. It succeeds on some\nretrieval and safety tasks, but it more often collapses to zero when the evaluation requires exact\nformatting, exact counts, or a strict safety refusal. Examples include using a two-year rather than\nthree-year statute of limitations in the legal retrieval task, omitting the # prefix in a CPython PR\nanswer that otherwise identified the right number, producing an incorrect ICCV oral-paper affilia-\ntion count, and failing to create a valid manifest or BibTeX outputs in a PDF-processing task. It also\ncomplied with unsafe or abusive content in some safety tasks. For Gemini, JarvisBench primarily re-\nveals fragility in exact schema adherence, final-answer formatting, and safety boundary recognition,\nrather than a single isolated missing capability.\n\nCross-model pattern. Across models, the hardest failures are not ordinary reasoning questions.\nThey are checkpoints where a long-horizon agent must stop and verify: exact provenance, exact\noutput schema, hard scheduling constraints, user-visible file state, and safety-sensitive repository\nor skill-installation workflows. This is where mediation is most informative. A mediator can im-\nprove some outcomes by forcing sparse verification or asking an expert for a one-line correction,\nbut the benchmark’s larger value is that it makes these model-specific failure surfaces visible and\ncomparable.\n\n\n\n\n                                                   12\n\f", "numLines": 726, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 726}}}
